    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-03-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-03-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="734"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d734">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6329</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-03-11">March 11,
                            1937</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I think this telegram<note n="45" xml:id="d734fn45">See letter from the Secretary
                        of State to President Roosevelt, March 2, <ref target="#pg_571">p.
                        571</ref>; for telegram as sent to the Ambassador in the United Kingdom, see
                            <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>.</note> in regard to the China Consortium
                    goes much too far. I have, therefore, struck out the paragraphs that seem to me
                    unnecessary. I do not think it is necessary for us to give approval at this late
                    date to the old Consortium agreement, especially in the way it has worked
                    out.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>F[<hi rend="smallcaps">ranklin</hi>] D. R[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >oosevelt</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
